column11: Elections for the next mayor of London will be held on 5 May 2016. The main candidates are Zac Goldsmith of the Conservatives and Sadiq Khan of Labour (The World in 2016). The mayor of London is responsible for a budget of Â£17 billion, with powers over transport, housing, economic development, the environment, and the arts (London Elects). Recommended Question Before 1 May 2016, will Britain set a date for a referendum on EU membership? Will a member of the National League for Democracy (NLD) take office as president of Myanmar before April 2016? Who will win Uganda's next presidential election?

Khan isn't a particularly well-known or charismatic politician, but he's a Labour candidate for mayor in a predominantly Labour city, perhaps the only place where Corbyn's leadership of the party might be seen as anything other than a liability. Boris's two election victories were won against the backdrop of a spectacularly unpopular Labour government (08) and a bitter, divisive Ken Livingstone campaign (2012). This time, the Conservatives will have been in power for 6 years by the time of the election, and despite a very healthy national polling lead, are vulnerable to a protest vote in London. Goldsmith has the same weaknesses as Khan, but without Boris's pre-existing national profile.

If Khan the Sensible Labourite (cf. Bill Clinton) can continue to distance himself from Labour's illustrious leader--the really crazy version of Bernie Sanders--he should cruise into office. Probably he should stop accusing the Tories of being anti-Islamic, though; sounds whiny.

It might be expected that an election for London Mayor would attract a protest vote coming a year after a General Election in which the Conservatives won (unexpectedly) and Labour did badly, but while a very Old Labour (Corbyn) was elected the new party leader with strong support grass roots support the elections for the labour mayoral candidate seem to have stuck with a Milliband type candidate (SK). So I don't expect any radical candidate to break through in London. The Mayor actually has few powers except for transport so the election is unlikely to attract voters who expect to change the world. The problems that the Labour Party has with splits in policies, although these are not particularly policies related to the job of mayor, are likely to reduce the enthusiasm of Labour supports who might struggle to understand what Labour now stands for. ZG is another rich posh boy, that sounds like a disadvantage in a city that naturally leans left but Boris got elected twice. We also need to take account of the fact that Labour supporters are easier to find on the street and more likely to be polled than Conservative supporter, so opinion polls are not reliable.

I adjusted the probability upward (10%) as the Labour party seem to have strong support in London, consistent with the notion of an urban-rural political divide in US, UK, and Canada, which had become starker recently. I also see SK's working class background and ethnicity as advantageous traits for garnering additional popular support, and a factor in mobilizing otherwise apathetic voters, at the same time, ZG's socio-economic background may isolate him from voters who do not share the same privileges, in combination, I assign a higher likelihood (5%) of SK's election. In terms of policy, SK's platform seem more comprehensive and detailed, and aim more towards affordability; ZG's seem more abbreviated, for anyone who actually look at the policies to make a decision, I think a better laid out plan would appeal to a completely neutral voter (2% for SK?).

London is a Labour stronghold, and if anything has become more so. It's more or less the only place in the country that, in aggregate, probably doesn't mind Jeremy Corbyn as Labour leader (elsewhere he is very widely regarded as a naive idiot). Khan is a solid candidate with no obvious blots on his record, and provided he doesn't screw up, he should win. Yes, Tory Boris Johnson won the last two mayoral elections, but Boris is an exceptional politician with a gift for being liked that manages to cross political divides. Zac is a good retail politician, as well as being smart & likeable (he took a marginal seat in Richmond and over 2 elections has turned it solidly Tory), but Boris he is not.
